						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Stone set up near the village gate.</hi></p>						

						<p>Dēvarāya I—A.D. 1407.</p>						

						<p>This inscription, referring itself to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Dēvarāya,</hi> son of <hi rend="bold">Harihara-Mahārāya,</hi> is dated in <hi rend="bold">Śaka 1329, Sarvajit, Āśvayuja śu. 10, Sunday,</hi> corresponding regularly to <hi rend="bold">A.D. 1407, September 11, Sunday f.d.t. 23.</hi></p>						

						<p>It states that <hi rend="bold">Midarasa,</hi> son of <hi rend="italic">Sēnādhipati</hi> <hi rend="bold">Saṁgama</hi> installed an image of <hi rend="bold">Kumāra Rāmanāthadēva</hi> in <hi rend="bold">Cheṅgāpura</hi> (modern Saṅgūr), situated in <hi rend="bold">Chandragutt-ināḍu</hi> of the <hi rend="bold">Gōve-rājya.</hi> <hi rend="italic">Sēnādhipati</hi> Saṁgama is stated to be the grandson of <hi rend="bold">Bayichaveggaḷe</hi> who was the <hi rend="italic">Bahattaraniyōgādhipati</hi> of <hi rend="bold">Kampilarāya.</hi></p>						

						<p>It is noteworthy that Dēvarāya is given the titles of <hi rend="bold">Chālukya</hi> monarchs. (Published in <hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.,</hi> Vol. XXIII, pp. 182 ff.).</p>						

						</summary>
